column11: The U.S. federal funds rate is the interest rate charged for overnight lending among financial institutions with accounts at the Federal Reserve and sets the base rate for borrowing costs across the financial system (Investopedia). The target for the federal funds rate is set by the Federal Open Market Committee. The March meeting is scheduled for 14-15 March 2017. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

What will the Federal Open Market Committee decide to do with respect to the federal funds rate at its scheduled March 2017 meeting? Forecast: Raise 80 %, Maintain 20% and lower 0%. The information shown in figure 1 is the monthly development in the effective federal funds rate since July 1954. Remarkable are the peaks of the funds rate in the eighties (maximum? When?) and the extreme minimums around 2010 (minimum? When?). As becomes clear from the graph the development of the federal funds rate is divided in increasing and decreasing trends, the trends lasts for several months and sometimes years. This implies that if the effective federal funds rate has risen in the previous month, the probability of an increase in the rate in the next month is higher than the chance of a decrease. Therefore it becomes useful to look at the most recent trend. Figure 2 shows clearly a gradually increasing trend in the effective federal funds rate. This increase started in November 2015, with a rate just above 0.1% and is was between 0,6% and 0,7% in the most recent data. The trend does not seem to have reached it’s peak yet, since it is still gradually increasing until January 2017. However, the question is not about the effective federal funds rate, but about the targeted federal fund rate by the Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC). The decision to use the data of the effective federal funds rate can be justified by showing that the effective federal funds rate usually follow the targeted federal funds rate. If one compares figure 2 & 3, it becomes clear that when the FOMC decided to raise the limit if of the target rate from 0,25% to 0,5% in January 2016, the effective rate increased quickly to a rate just below 0.4% and continued to increase slowly after that time. A similar development is shown when the FOMC raised the limit of the target rate to 0,75% in the end of 2016. Thus, these two figures highly correlate with each other and therefore the effective federal funds rate can be used as an indicator of the targeted federal funds rate by the FOMC.
